 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBringing together leading scholars from Asia and the West, this book investigates how the dynamics of China’s rise in world politics contributes to theory-building in International Relations (IR). The book demonstrates how the complex and transformative nature of China’s advancement is also a point of departure for theoretical innovation and reflection in IR more broadly. In doing so, the volume builds a strong case for a genuinely global and post-Western IR. It contends that ‘non-Western’ countries should not only be considered potential sources of knowledge production, but also original and legitimate focuses of IR theorizing in their own right.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aAgnew, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBunskoek, Raoul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuzan, Barry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHwang, Yih-Jye, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJisi, Wang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKavalski, Emilian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKavalski, Emilian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLing, L.H.M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcNally, Christopher A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNordin, Astrid H.M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPan, Chengxin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPan, Chengxin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r